40:00.809 --> 40:03.314
You know, some of them are treasures, some of them are not.

40:03.855 --> 40:07.381
No, I actually have not seen a real treasure yet.

40:07.401 --> 40:09.345
I haven't either.

40:09.365 --> 40:10.527
But I happen to...

40:10.827 --> 40:12.351
have an eye for treasures, you know.

40:13.735 --> 40:15.359
I wrote a book on that set.

40:15.379 --> 40:15.600
Right.

40:16.041 --> 40:21.094
And people love, people find fascinating things in bookstores that are treasures, you know.

40:21.415 --> 40:22.478
They buy for a buck.

40:22.839 --> 40:26.188
But what bothers me, I guess, is nobody can tell you the title.

40:26.308 --> 40:27.030
I mean, there's

40:27.213 --> 40:31.459
There doesn't even seem to be a record of the books that were... Probably not.

40:31.499 --> 40:35.224
I don't want people who went to Auschwitz and we can use people a record of the name.

40:35.684 --> 40:38.809
I mean, a book is a living thing to a lot of us.

40:39.450 --> 40:47.180
Well, I'll tell you, once you discard something, first of all, if it's on the... It doesn't seem like it was systematic discarding.

40:47.200 --> 40:48.922
It seems like it was wholesale dumping.

40:49.163 --> 40:49.603
Could have been.

40:50.565 --> 40:50.965
Could have been.

40:51.005 --> 40:52.547
I mean, to call a spade a spade.

40:52.567 --> 40:53.969
Yeah, it could have been, frankly.

40:54.290 --> 40:56.072
This library didn't weed for years.

40:56.710 --> 41:03.377
They suffered from the fact that they moved from that building across the street over here without doing a systematic weeding program.

41:03.957 --> 41:07.521
And so then there was just all kinds of chaos, I understand.

41:07.541 --> 41:09.282
I don't know how true this is.

41:09.302 --> 41:10.744
These are just stories I've heard.

41:11.324 --> 41:11.725
Who knows?

41:11.785 --> 41:12.726
Panic, chaos.

41:13.166 --> 41:13.566
Who knows?

41:13.627 --> 41:25.418
But if you don't have a systematic weeding program so that you are evaluating the collection on a regular, systematic basis,

41:25.702 --> 41:28.185
And we've done all the work for it.

41:28.245 --> 41:30.028
We've got a collection maintenance program.

41:30.348 --> 41:31.670
We have a collection development.

41:32.871 --> 41:34.593
Staff has worked on these for years.

41:35.314 --> 41:41.022
But what they haven't done, and they always say they don't have time to do, is they don't have time to do the weeding.

41:42.043 --> 41:45.087
Just as you weed your garden, you've got to weed your collection.

41:46.268 --> 41:53.217
And I found that in Berkeley, if you didn't stay on people's backs about it, it didn't happen.

41:53.337 --> 41:54.679
It's not a lot of fun.

41:55.267 --> 41:57.590
It's the easiest thing to let slide.

41:57.610 --> 42:01.035
It's the easiest thing to let slide, and that is what happened here.

42:02.697 --> 42:05.841
And that's not the whole problem, but it contributes to it.

42:05.861 --> 42:20.762
It seems to me that there are probably about six or eight different factors, all of which in themselves are not huge, but by putting them together got the library to this issue where they said thousands of books were destroyed.

42:21.282 --> 42:22.143
Who the hell knows?

42:22.163 --> 42:22.624
I don't know.

42:22.992 --> 42:42.942
I know when you've got a catalog and you pull catalog cards, the way we were always taught in library school to pull catalog cards was, well, this one doesn't have a pocket, but, you know, you go to the catalog, you pull out the six or eight cards that go with it, you stick it in the pocket, you send the book away.

42:43.723 --> 42:44.925
There goes the record.

42:45.926 --> 42:51.615
Now, the only thing that the library might even have paid attention to, if they took the trouble to do it,

42:51.916 --> 42:53.398
would be the accession records.

42:53.939 --> 42:55.501
The accession records.

42:55.521 --> 43:06.817
Yeah, well, a lot of times if people kept accession records, if people kept shelf lists, that's what it's called, sometimes if you were really paying attention, you'd go in and you'd cross off the ones that had been discarded.

43:08.159 --> 43:09.621
I don't even know if that was done here.

43:09.821 --> 43:11.303
I don't know if there was a shelf list.

43:12.365 --> 43:19.054
In terms of those that were on the catalog, unless there was a last...

43:19.878 --> 43:22.602
You would not know, because there are no cards to pull.

43:22.622 --> 43:24.364
Or you'd know that there wasn't a copy anymore.

43:24.404 --> 43:25.385
You wouldn't know which.

43:26.146 --> 43:27.027
You know, it's wiped.

43:27.448 --> 43:28.709
It goes, it's erased.

43:29.170 --> 43:38.943
Do you have a sense of the feeling of a public library, a city public library, as being a repository as a research library?

43:38.963 --> 43:40.245
This isn't a research library.

43:42.548 --> 43:43.509
Even in any areas?

43:43.929 --> 43:45.491
Might be in San Francisco history.

43:46.232 --> 43:48.315
Might be a research library in art and music.

43:49.004 --> 43:50.486
But we are not a research library.

43:50.506 --> 43:53.309
There isn't a research library, I believe, west of the Mississippi.

43:54.890 --> 43:58.474
If you look at the criteria... In terms of a public library?

43:58.494 --> 43:59.535
In terms of a library.

44:00.456 --> 44:02.038
I think a library is a research library.

44:02.058 --> 44:04.260
Yes, it is, but it's... In terms of a research library?

44:04.280 --> 44:05.221
Not necessarily.

44:08.385 --> 44:11.228
There is no public library that's a research library.

44:12.429 --> 44:13.931
And San Francisco isn't one.

44:14.371 --> 44:16.193
And we don't have the money to become one.

44:16.612 --> 44:23.002
Because in order to become a research library, there's something called the Association of Research Libraries.

44:24.464 --> 44:30.754
And there are certain criteria they have for depth of collections and for the kinds of things that are kept.

44:30.854 --> 44:31.695
And we don't meet that.

44:32.897 --> 44:34.239
What's that about association?

44:34.519 --> 44:37.063
A-R-L, Association of Research Libraries.

44:38.866 --> 44:39.367
Why don't you?

44:39.407 --> 44:40.909
I think that would be useful for you.

44:42.131 --> 44:42.231
Yeah.

44:42.903 --> 44:45.766
Yes, in terms of San Francisco history, sure.

44:45.986 --> 44:48.268
We should have the best possible collection available.

44:48.769 --> 44:53.173
We should have an excellent collection of Californiana as well, and I think we do.

44:53.193 --> 44:57.817
We have some rare books, but we don't have a rare book library, per se.

44:58.638 --> 45:00.660
Nothing like what UC has, for instance.

45:02.202 --> 45:03.703
Or the New York Public Library.

45:03.843 --> 45:05.685
Or the Boston Public Library, right.

45:06.506 --> 45:07.447
Or Cleveland, or Chicago.

45:07.467 --> 45:07.767
Right.

45:08.328 --> 45:09.889
We are not that big a library.

45:10.561 --> 45:13.344
San Francisco isn't that big a city, if you think about it.

45:15.787 --> 45:19.330
We're a good reference library.

45:19.671 --> 45:20.572
That's the difference.

45:21.392 --> 45:32.004
We can probably answer 95% of the questions that somebody might come in to ask here, and answer that at some level of depth.

45:32.724 --> 45:38.070
But we would not be able to provide research materials to

45:40.362 --> 45:44.991
but we wouldn't be able to provide research material at the same level.

45:46.012 --> 45:58.415
In other words, we could answer your question, you know, who killed Cockwabin, but we wouldn't be able to give you the exhaustive material for the background of that particular question.

46:00.299 --> 46:03.585
We're probably the library, public library,

46:04.240 --> 46:10.828
Northern California, we're probably the strongest public library in Northern California in terms of collection size and breadth and depth.

46:13.211 --> 46:15.794
We're not as big as Los Angeles, you know.

46:16.755 --> 46:17.276
That's a much bigger city.

46:17.296 --> 46:17.936
Much bigger city.

46:17.956 --> 46:18.897
Have you visited that one?

46:19.578 --> 46:19.738
Not yet.

46:19.759 --> 46:20.459
You ought to go there.

46:21.441 --> 46:30.231
They did an extremely nice job in taking a 1927-29 building

46:30.768 --> 46:32.650
which was a landmark in adding on.

46:32.951 --> 46:34.353
They had a fire, too.

46:34.413 --> 46:35.494
Yeah, they had a terrible fire.

46:35.855 --> 46:37.757
But they were in worse shape than we were.

46:38.338 --> 46:40.000
Oh, they were in really very circus shape.

46:40.020 --> 46:41.582
Yeah, yeah.

46:41.662 --> 46:45.267
I'm going down in a couple of weeks to talk to the director.

46:45.467 --> 46:49.172
But, you know, they have more depth than we do.

46:51.635 --> 46:55.240
We are a popular, well, we are a number of things.

46:55.844 --> 46:58.568
In the branch libraries, we're a popular library.

46:58.608 --> 47:07.180
We're a reference library for high school students and for use by interested citizens.

47:07.760 --> 47:10.524
We're a library that serves a lot of children.

47:11.205 --> 47:15.371
You know, our Discovery Center here in this main library is a wonderful place.

47:16.292 --> 47:24.383
And it's particularly wonderful with the increase in population of children down here from, you know...

47:25.477 --> 47:31.366
Southeast Asia, yeah, because there's no place for these kids to go.

47:31.667 --> 47:33.489
We're a pretty good reference library here.

47:34.511 --> 47:37.496
We provide a lot of quick information, and we do a lot of programming.

47:38.477 --> 47:52.699
So we're kind of, I would say, pretty much middle-of-the-road urban library, with all of the urban library problems, all the problems that an urban library faces.

47:53.337 --> 48:03.369
So usage of material or non-usage is a criterion that probably might influence whether or not a book is kept.

48:03.389 --> 48:06.973
If a book hasn't been read, say, in two or three or four or five years.

48:07.353 --> 48:09.256
That would be a criteria, yeah.

48:10.137 --> 48:13.481
And for us also, in certain areas, the age of the material.

48:14.902 --> 48:16.304
You know, particularly in science.

48:17.866 --> 48:21.570
Why would we be wanting to have a book that says someday we will get to the moon?

48:22.812 --> 48:23.192
You know?

48:23.678 --> 48:27.482
It's not where we want to be necessarily.

48:27.503 --> 48:29.665
You're writing some social history, though, and you want to know what people thought about that.

48:29.685 --> 48:32.208
That's true, but then we can get that for you.

48:33.229 --> 48:37.554
We can interlibrary loan material from anywhere in the country, and we do.

48:38.596 --> 48:39.817
And that's the kind of material.

48:39.837 --> 48:46.064
There's a regional storage facility over in Richmond that the University of California has for its little-used material.

48:46.104 --> 48:49.228
We can borrow from them just like that, no problems.

48:50.069 --> 48:52.572
It takes a couple of weeks sometimes, but we can get it.

48:53.294 --> 49:11.881
What I find is that the major urban libraries, like the large supermarkets, have 80% of the use of the collection comes from 20% of the collection.

49:11.901 --> 49:19.652
And you'll find that in a large supermarket, 80% of their sales are 20% of the items that they stock.

49:19.732 --> 49:20.733
That's just the way it goes.

49:20.793 --> 49:22.035
The other 80%

49:22.285 --> 49:24.809
are there and are used a lot less.

49:25.309 --> 49:28.534
And that's where the decision to weed is so important.

49:29.035 --> 49:38.288
And that's why weeding a collection has to be done by people who know the collection, know the use patterns, and understand the community.

49:39.309 --> 49:44.937
